            "fact_text": "<h2>Earrings</h2><ul><li>Earrings are among the oldest body adornments ever discovered. The earliest known earrings date back over 7,000 years, worn by ancient Sumerians and found in the royal graves of Ur.<br/></li><li>In ancient civilizations, earrings showed tribe, profession and even political loyalty. Egyptians believed adorning the ears made them more visible to gods and protected them spiritually.<br/></li><li>In ancient and medieval Europe, gold earrings were thought to strengthen vision and sailors wore them believing the metal protected their eyes on long voyages.<br/></li><li>Greek women wore golden hoops and pendants, Romans took it further with pearls that became symbols of extreme wealth. Julius Caesar even passed a law controlling their use.<br/></li><li>Earrings were once worn more by men than women. Warriors, sailors, kings and tribes across Asia and Europe wore earrings to show courage, achievements and rites of passage.</li></ul>"
